The book we're talking about here is very unusual - the author describes it himself, quite at best, as an "antihistory work".
It contains several very familiar names, important contracts or famous battles, on the contrary, almost lacking ambassadors, energetic journalists and debates on tactics and equipment.
It's not even a book about what happened, the author explains, rather, "book about what it was like." He deals mainly with "feelings, perceptions, experiences and moods."
"Beautiful and saddening" combines the war experiences of 20 fewer dozen men and women, on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives crumble like the flames of candles lit in the church - new ones are added to the complexion of fate while others are put out.
The book of Mr. Englund differs from the classic historical novels.
It governs the idea that the first world war was just about the terrible trenches on the Western front.
"Beautiful and saddening" has been looking into other places where war dramas were taking place: Alps, Balkans, Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with falling bees' nests, having to spend Christmas in the shade of pyramids or facing the presence of much tse-tse.
