Walls have eyes: How scientists examine you on Facebook
Before Anders Behring Breivik became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, he was just another young man who presented his anti-immigration views on the Internet.
On Monday, Braivik, who confessed to July’s murderous rage, which left 77 dead in Norway, took part in his first public court hearing.
Although Breivik was able to act alone, he was not alone in cyberspace: during the preparation of the attack, he spent a lot of time with the computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting the right-wing group on social networks websites.
After the tragedy of this year, scientists want to know more about these people.
But how do I find them?
Easy, enough to go to Facebook.
"We realized that getting to them is not really that hard," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report by the British research team on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so comprehensive, says Bartlett, that scientists have been able to easily use advertising on the website and, thanks to this, have determined with complete accuracy the search for a demographic group - something that marketing workers have been doing for years.
Throughout Europe, the Bartlett team has found half a million right-wing fans, focusing on them and sending out ads to them, but instead of calling them into a newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they have called them to fill out a questionnaire asking questions about the level of their education, the relationship to violence and optimism in view of their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without having to leave the office at all.
"It is a completely new way of carrying out research," notes Bartlett.
Some of the results are not as surprising: online right-wing supporters are all young men, who promote a growing rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with off-line activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind the screen of the computer."
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists and political researchers use these pages to study everything, from health problems to social trends, which include state updates, contributions to the walls and "I like them" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them will provide on average three different data on a daily basis, making this social network literally "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new research. The number of academic work in which the word Facebook appears has risen to almost 800% over five years ago.
For some scientists, Facebook's magic is that it gives them the opportunity to study people without having to bother them somewhere on the street.
"It used to be true that when you wanted to do research among the people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to the side where you'd never be let go," Bartlett says.
"This whole Facebook thing is breaking down - you're just going straight to them."
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify the social-health problem and avoid them.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of the University of Wisconsin, the research team found that university students who were discussing their drunken performances on Facebook were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about the subject.
Moren suggests that the peers of the students’ pages monitor and come with a offer of help to a student who publishes too much drunken status.
"The problem cannot be solved unless you can diagnose it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Morena and Director of the Centre for Health, Behavior and Development at the Child Research Institute in Seattle.
"We found a way to identify the children at risk that we would not have a chance to discover otherwise."
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The information team of the website has developed statistics on the relationship between the status relationship and the date of St. Valentine's Day, the electoral participation in 2010 and the coefficient of satisfaction of the nation (mainly by using information they have had access to - Internet freedom advocates have long argued that the website should make its information treasure available to research and others).
But Facebook users know that the website is watching whether they like it or not - in exchange for the opportunity to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometers away, you need to provide your personal information.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect off-line data. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
"I don't think most of the users could even think that scientists could look at their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist in London Knowleddge Lab, about a study from 2006, which he conducted using the public facebook walls of his students.
"If it was about them, they took it so that the information was just between them and their friends."
Subsequently, it is also important to consider the question of methodology.
Even in the off-line research, there is no guarantee that the entity is completely honest.
