The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has initiated research on a gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to find the gene responsible for the obesity of children and adolescents. The research is carried out with the support of experts from the Institute of IPN.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to detect a gene causing obesity in children and young people. A research entitled "Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents" will enable you to obtain results on overweight.
In a report by Head of the Biochemistry Research Unit of the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Centre of the 21st century Miguel Cruz López explained that a multidisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutrition experts and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and from the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Institute of Polytechnics (IPN).
People can also participate in research by a wide public, with or without a right. People can come to the IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where they will conduct youth tests in every congregation from 8 hours.
He stressed that research had started in the Cuauhtémo Sports Centre (Mexico State) and that since 8 October this activity was also carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
As soon as data are available from 500 to 600 children, the study will continue at the Independent Sports Centre (beyond the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north from the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and significance of genetics in the development of obesity and to trace to Mexican children and young people the risk factors and thus prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Day of Diabetes, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He pointed out that each Saturday with all participants carried out anthropometric measurements (weight, height, range), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin, and gene testing (the genes involved in child obesity are being identified).
Cruz López said that this research reflects the concerns of health professionals over the alarming increase in child weight.
'Health polls between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, boys only experienced an increase in obesity by 77% and girls by 47%.
He said that one reason for finding indicators is that the population of the country differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African, which is reflected in the genes responsible for diabetes and overweight.
He explained that obesity is generally explained as an inability to burn excess energy, which we consume (calorie) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants was that they would be given an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thus finding out whether they were exhibiting any known weights or obesity.
He said that even the presence of dark color wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearm suggests the likelihood that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetes.
The information is confidential so far, doctors hand it over to their parents in writing and explain to them all the measurements and changes in lifestyles they must make to avoid their children’s disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle marked by a lack of daily physical activity, a full-day sit-in before television and the use of means of transport instead of walking at short distances.
The weight is also caused by a large calorie intake, which is a larger consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and a genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
